<main id="content">
  <article class="prose">
    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>Design &amp; Craft</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        This page looks at how nature-inspired, eco-conscious jewelry is actually made:
        from material choices to design decisions and final finishing details.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>Design Philosophy</h2>
      <p>
        Nature-inspired jewelry is built around contrast: raw textures next to polished metal,
        organic shapes against clean lines. Designers study crystals, geodes, and mineral patterns
        and use them as the starting point for each piece. Instead of forcing stones into a rigid,
        “perfect” shape, many eco-luxury pieces celebrate the natural edges and color variations.
      </p>
      <p>
        This design approach works well for sustainable brands because it reduces waste. Rather than
        discarding stones that don’t look perfectly uniform, designers work with what already exists
        and let the piece follow the stone’s shape and character.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Materials and Processes</h2>
      <p>
        Reclaimed gold is melted down, refined, and recast into new settings. This allows designers
        to create fresh pieces without depending on new mining. Recycled diamonds and gemstones are
        re-cut or re-set into updated styles, giving existing stones a second life.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bench jewelers still play a huge role in this process. Even if the design begins digitally,
        the final work at the bench—soldering, setting, polishing, and adding patina—is what turns
        simple materials into something that feels personal and long-lasting.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Finish, Patina, and Longevity</h2>
      <p>
        The finish of a piece matters just as much as the materials. A high polish can feel classic
        and formal, while a matte or brushed finish gives a softer, more organic vibe. Patina can be
        added intentionally to highlight texture or contrast different areas of the metal.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because sustainable jewelry is meant to last, designers think about repair and resizing from
        the beginning. Well-built settings, solid bands, and accessible stone mounts make it easier
        for a piece to be adjusted and worn for years instead of being replaced.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</main>
